{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T18:58:53.922331+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-06T19:11:17.287404+00:00", "id": 13529502, "conceptrecid": "13529501", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13529502", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13529501", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13529502", "metadata": {"title": "Eptesicus fuscus Orthorubulavirus, a Close Relative of Human Parainfluenza Virus 4, Discovered in a Bat in South Dakota", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13529502", "publication_date": "2021", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Bats are a reservoir for many zoonotic viruses and host large numbers of genetically diverse species in the families Rhabdoviridae, Coronaviridae, and Paramyxoviridae. Viruses from these families have repeatedly spilled over to humans in recent decades, causing significant clinical disease and deaths. Here, metagenomic sequencing of a big brown bat (Eptesicus fuscus) submitted for rabies testing due to human exposure identified a novel paramyxovirus, Eptesicus fuscus orthorubulavirus (EfORV), in South Dakota, United States. The nearly complete 15,814-nucleotide genome shared 72% identity with that of human parainfluenza virus 4 (HPIV4), a virus that causes significant clinical disease, typically bronchiolitis and pneumonia, in children less than 2 years of age. Phylogenetic analysis confirmed a close evolutionary history between EfORV and HPIV4, reminiscent of other orthorubulaviruses with highly similar bat and mammalian species, including conspecific human and bat mumps virus, mammalian parainfluenza virus 5 and bat Alston virus, and porcine La Piedad Michoac\u00e1n virus and bat Mapuera virus. These results support the idea that bats are a reservoir for diverse paramyxoviruses with closely shared evolutionary histories, compared with a number of significant human pathogens, and expand the range of bat paramyxoviruses to North America. Given the propensity of paramyxoviruses to overcome species barriers, additional surveillance and characterization of EfORV are warranted.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Hause, Ben M.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Nelson, Eric", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Christopher-Hennings, Jane", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Martin, Rebekah M.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/bbced968d5f6840ebfe062f44cd6a9aa", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/35dd784809ae478bcf0ebf2792b3ddd53fc17dfd7b00e3de9045c0207bbe0e92", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/L5RJHU33", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/L5RJHU33", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/f28e086149b12c34ba2baa6a243fc08c!/b37182-39642", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "2", "pages": "e00930-21", "title": "Microbiology Spectrum", "volume": "9"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/bbced968d5f6840ebfe062f44cd6a9aa"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:L5RJHU33"}, {"identifier": "10.1128/Spectrum.00930-21"}], "communities": [{"id": "biosyslit"}, {"id": "batlit"}], "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "13529501"}}]}}, "title": "Eptesicus fuscus Orthor